    <h2>Good Faith Journalism</h2><br>
    <p id="07e61d6e-db2c-4809-afa7-97919c0a0ae1" class=""></p>
    <p id="9ec69352-9f4b-4ac3-9b16-6ec7d6f2fb45" class="">I often encounter people who are overwhelmed in terms of evaluating and consuming information in this era of high political tensions, unlimited potential sources, and the vast evolution of the media landscape. How can we identify what I like to call 'good faith' actors or reporters? 'Good faith' would mean simply that the entity reporting or providing the information isn't entirely motivated by the information being interpreted within their narrow viewpoint. It means they are not intentionally taking liberties with the accuracy or integrity of the info for the purpose of driving a narrative. </p><br>
    <p id="9ae0f1d4-113a-4954-bb8b-772057dc4433" class="">Generally, 'good faith' is the ability to see all the way around an idea and being more motivated by journalistic accuracy than journalistic activism. In almost all forms of media reporting we inevitably have to take reporting at faith, meaning we have no way to personally verify what's being said. If we have to take them at faith then in an ideal situation they would be reporting and practicing journalism in good faith. In good faith in this context means their goal as a journalist is optimizing truth and to provide information that is as accurate as possible. </p><br>
    <p id="c789c8d8-9e59-4226-8178-d6d96e675a6c" class="">Problems arise once the motivation shifts from the desire to report the events and facts as factually and unopinionated as possible to a journalistic desire that is similar to an activist where the motivation behind reporting is the desire to have the reader reach specific conclusion, the same one which informs the journalists perspective. The reporting becomes less an unemotional description of what and how events occurred and more a narrative-driven interpretation of the meaning derived from the events. The application or meaning to anything in life is a function of interpretation through our unique perspectives. It is insulting honestly and rude for someone else to saturate a story in context that implies a specific meaning. It's insulting because the reason they do it is because they believe their formed views or opinions are RIGHT or CORRECT and they don’t trust you to come to the same conclusions on your own. Realistically views and opinions are in fact SUBJECTIVE matters. </p><br>
    <p id="b30146d5-c00a-47ba-87df-53974363e7fd" class="">There's certainly nothing wrong with opinion pieces, especially when prefaced as such or providing a subjective perspective on something to an audience when it's clear that's what's being provided - I would consider this entertainment media. The problem I have is entertainment platforms which try to give the appearance of providing classical journalistic news, which historically has been more trustworthy due to a track record of accuracy and objectivity, and then inject narrative, bias and general subjectivity under the guise that it's objective.</p><br><hr>
    <h2 id="342dd377-6fd6-4d68-8260-9b7d1d9414b0" class="">How can we tell?</h2><br>
    <ul id="ea9da840-96ab-450a-8152-d30c6355bdbb" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">How balanced is the journalist or platform in terms of the scope of all reporting done?</li>
    </ul>
    <ul id="ed24e73a-8689-4f09-976b-6bb6008e35f8" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">How balanced is the journalist or platform in terms of the language used in its reporting?</li>
    </ul>
    <ul id="e56713e8-835d-4e08-8f4c-f00f1341204d" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">How balanced is the journalist or platform in terms of its opinion to facts ratio?</li>
    </ul>
    <ul id="d9332159-e53f-48d8-bbd6-e9617f9e09ad" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">Is there a skew towards subjective conclusions? Conveying emotion or using emotionally charged language?</li>
    </ul>
    <ul id="950679c0-2fa8-45a5-a406-98d94856bff3" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">Do they explore ideas in a meandering grey area or do ideas often seem black and white?</li>
    </ul>
    <ul id="2217079b-a250-4875-8f1e-8fc46b6b5226" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">Notice the difference between black and white, and a tendency to use the same blacks and whites and thoroughly exploring both the black and the white on any given idea or subject. The latter is more indicative of good faith reporting seeking to optimize accuracy because they are willing to explore both sides of an idea equally, in a way that masks their true proclivity. The less you are aware of what a reporter truly believes, likely the more objective they are. If you already have an idea of a reporter's leanings even before reading a report, it's likely they have a subjective tendency.</li>
    </ul>
    <ul id="333cf155-71da-4be2-a4bf-763aab991ade" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">Try to identify a writer's intention. Do you notice an emotional state arising or being evoked? Is that clearly the intention? And why? Or does no particular intention outside of being informative become apparent? What kind of intention do you desire from the entities that are curating and providing the information you consume? In my experience (notice the explicit distinction of subjective/anecdotal experience) consuming media through these filters has led me to develop a stronger judgment of character and a greater ability to properly contextualize information. The source and the source's intent or motive in providing the information matter greatly. Do you want your information to come from a source who wants you to believe something particular (what they believe) or a source who has no concern as to what you believe? Why? Is one more inherently trustworthy than the other?</li><br>
    </ul>
