    <h3 id="6cd11031-9748-40c5-b21b-0ecc0ce2f936" class="">My final thoughts and analysis of Media Matters as a greater entity that curates and publishes information for public consumption </h3><br><hr>
    <p id="326e8510-d1f7-452b-b40f-7f40e5a2c53d" class="">
      <strong>Lacks Balanced Reporting:</strong>
    </p>
    <ul id="1925e385-c162-4c4b-a2f7-5856ee0004a7" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">
        <strong>Selective reporting:</strong> Media Matters has been criticized for focusing on negative stories about conservative media outlets while ignoring or downplaying negative stories about liberal media outlets. A 2018 study by the Media Research Center found that Media Matters covered negative stories about Fox News at a rate of 50 to 1 compared to negative stories about CNN.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <ul id="c89cff02-bfef-4496-acee-01c9c27c7f9f" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">
        <strong>Misrepresentation of facts:</strong> Media Matters has been accused of misrepresenting facts and taking quotes out of context in order to support its narrative. For example, in 2012, Media Matters was forced to retract a story after it was revealed that the organization had edited a video of Rush Limbaugh to make it appear as if he was calling for violence against women.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <ul id="e8f127a4-05a6-4c03-b0c4-a5cb5a991e0a" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">
        <strong>Omission of relevant information:</strong> Media Matters has been criticized for omitting relevant information from its reporting in order to make its targets look bad. For example, in 2017, Media Matters published a story about a speech by then-President Donald Trump that omitted key parts of the speech that would have provided context for his remarks.
      </li><br>
    </ul>
    <p id="33cdec24-d61b-4060-8e51-3b579240ae29" class="">
      <strong>Display of Extreme Bias:</strong>
    </p>
    <ul id="1251bed3-779d-4e6d-ae4e-17570d8fd125" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">
        <strong>Lack of transparency:</strong> Media Matters does not disclose its funding sources on its website. This lack of transparency makes it difficult to assess the organization's potential biases.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <ul id="927a6db3-66c1-4f16-8a30-a4e4fdf9568f" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">
        <strong>Association with partisan organizations:</strong> Media Matters has been criticized for its close ties to the Democratic Party. The organization has received funding from Democratic donors and has partnered with Democratic organizations on a number of projects.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <ul id="54709b43-1d2a-4e49-bfc8-464621ed2ba2" class="bulleted-list">
      <li style="list-style-type:disc">
        <strong>Use of loaded language:</strong> Media Matters frequently uses loaded language in its reporting, which can be seen as an attempt to influence public opinion. For example, the organization often uses terms like "hate speech" and "propaganda" to describe the speech of its targets.
